2.1 If you try to convert the cycle count data to tidy format (which you dont have to do for this assignment, because its hard), what is the main obstacle you will encounter?

We got the daily counts for bicycles passing certain points in the Auckland area from 2016 to 2018, so the records of these locations could be a little bit different from year to year. When we combine these three data frames into a single data frame, we may have multiple names for the same counter. But we do not have any standard rules to approach it, and we do not know how to deal with it as well. Also, there are some columns that are entire NA. Therefore, it is very hard to convert the cycle count data into a tidy format.

2.2 Compute the total number of cyclists counted for each day, and a suitable summary of the rainfall for each day, in the same data frame. Include justification the rainfall sumary you use.

## Choose the directory here which contain the three bike counter data files.
bike_files <- list.files("/Users/University\ of\ Auckland/Year\ 3/Semester\ 2/STATS\ 369/Assignment\ 1/Bikedata", pattern = ".csv", full = TRUE)

## Iterates over each element of `bike_files`, applying `read_csv` to each.
bike_data <- map(bike_files, read_csv)

## There are some columns that are entire `NA`: get rid of them with `select_if`.
notallNA <- function(x) !all(is.na(x))
## Apply the user defined function `notallNA` to each element of the list `bike_data`.
bike_data <- map(bike_data, select_if, notallNA)

## Try to `pivot_longer` for each data frame in `bike_data`.
bike_tidy <- map(bike_data, pivot_longer, values_to = "rider_count", names_to = "counter", -Date)
## Combine a list of data frames into a single data frame.
allbikes <- bind_rows(bike_tidy)

## Create a tibble with the number of active counters for each day.
active_allbikes <- allbikes %>% 
  filter(!is.na(rider_count)) %>% 
  count(Date) %>% 
  rename(number_of_active_counters = n)

## Create a tibble with the total number of cyclists counted for each day.
allbikes_day <- allbikes %>% 
  group_by(Date) %>% 
  summarise(daily_rider_count = sum(rider_count, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  left_join(active_allbikes, by = "Date") %>% 
  separate(col = Date, into = c("day of week", "day", "month", "year")) %>% 
  mutate(day = as.numeric(day), year = as.numeric(year)) %>% 
  mutate(month = case_when(month == "Jan" ~ 1, month == "Feb" ~ 2, month == "Mar" ~ 3, month == "Apr" ~ 4, 
                           month == "May" ~ 5, month == "Jun" ~ 6, month == "Jul" ~ 7, month == "Aug" ~ 8, 
                           month == "Sep" ~ 9, month == "Oct" ~ 10, month == "Nov" ~ 11, TRUE ~ 12))

The data frame bike_rainfall_day contains the total number of cyclists and the total amount of precipitation for each day from 2016 to 2018. For the rainfall summary statistic, I used the total amount of precipitation for each day. Such a summary statistic is commonly used to monitor the daily rainfall. But we have the hourly rainfall data from two different stations in Auckland, such as Albany (in North Auckland) and Mangere (in South Auckland), so I computed the total amount of precipitation for each station separately and took the average of them. It is an appropriate summary of the rainfall because it would be easier and more helpful to do further analysis between the number of cyclists and the amount of precipitation for each day in Auckland.

2.3 Draw suitable graphs to display how the number of cyclists varies over time, over season, over day of the week, and with rain.

## Modify the tibble `bike_rainfall_day` to get a new column called `date`.
bike_rainfall_day <- bike_rainfall_day %>% 
  mutate(date = paste(day, month, year, sep = "-")) %>% 
  mutate(date = as.Date(date, "%d-%m-%Y"))


## Draw a graphic to display the number of cyclists over time.
bike_rainfall_day %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = daily_rider_count)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "gam") + 
  labs(x = "Time", y = "Number of cyclists", 
       title = "The number of cyclists counted in Auckland from 2016 to 2018 (Time)") + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5))

The plot shows the number of cyclists counted in Auckland from Jan 2016 to Dec 2018. In general, the number of cyclists seems to decrease in the first half year but increases each year after June or July or August (Winter). For each year, there were more cyclists in Summer than in Winter.

## Create the tibble `bike_rainfall_season` with the factor variable called `season`.
y <- c("2016", "2017", "2018")
s <- c("Spring", "Summer", "Autumn", "Winter")
dow <- c("Mon", "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri", "Sat", "Sun")

bike_rainfall_season <- bike_rainfall_day %>% 
  mutate(season = case_when(month == 9 | month == 10 | month == 11 ~ "Spring", 
                            month == 12 | month == 1 | month == 2 ~ "Summer", 
                            month == 3 | month == 4 | month == 5 ~ "Autumn", 
                            TRUE ~ "Winter")) %>% 
  mutate(season = factor(season, levels = s), 
         `day of week` = factor(`day of week`, levels = dow), 
         year_fac = factor(year, levels = y))


## Draw a graphic to display the number of cyclists over season.
bike_rainfall_season %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = season, y = daily_rider_count)) + 
  geom_boxplot(fill = "red", alpha = 0.5) + 
  labs(x = "Season", y = "Number of cyclists", 
       title = "The number of cyclists counted in Auckland from 2016 to 2018 (Season)") + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5))

The box plot indicates that there seem to have fewer cyclists in Winter than in other seasons, which is consistent with the first plot (comments above).

## Draw a graphic to display the number of cyclists over day of the week.
bike_rainfall_season %>% 
  group_by(`day of week`) %>% 
  summarise(dow_count = sum(daily_rider_count)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = `day of week`, y = dow_count)) + 
  geom_col(aes(fill = `day of week`), color = "black") + 
  labs(x = "Day of Week", y = "Number of cyclists", 
       title = "The number of cyclists counted in Auckland from 2016 to 2018 (Day of Week)") + 
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Day of Week")) + 
  theme_classic() + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.3))

Overall, the number of cyclists increases each week from Monday to Tuesday but decreases after Tuesday. Most people rode bikes on Tuesdays more than on other working days in Auckland. For weekends, there were more cyclists on Sunday.

## The scatter plot to display the number of cyclists with rain.
bike_rainfall_season %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = total_amount_mm, y = daily_rider_count)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "gam") + 
  labs(x = "Amount of precipitation (mm)", y = "Number of cyclists", 
       title = "The number of cyclists and the rainfall in Auckland from 2016 to 2018") + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5))

## The hexagonal heatmap to display the number of cyclists with rain.
bike_rainfall_season %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = total_amount_mm, y = daily_rider_count)) + 
  geom_hex() + 
  labs(x = "Amount of precipitation (mm)", y = "Number of cyclists", 
       title = "The number of cyclists and the rainfall in Auckland from 2016 to 2018") + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5))

These two plots indicate a clear negative relationship between the number of cyclists and the amount of precipitation in Auckland from 2016 to 2018.

2.4 Fit a regression model to predict the number of cyclists from year, season, day of the week, and rain. You do not need to include interactions or transformation in the model, and results do not require cross-validation.

cyclists.fit <- lm(daily_rider_count ~ year_fac + season + `day of week` + total_amount_mm + 
                     number_of_active_counters, data = bike_rainfall_season)
plot(cyclists.fit, which = 1)

normcheck(cyclists.fit)

cooks20x(cyclists.fit)

summary(cyclists.fit)

We fitted a simple linear regression cyclists.fit to predict the number of cyclists from year, season, day of the week, rain, and the number of active counters. The number of active counters on each day does not seem to have a significant impact on the number of cyclists because the P-value of this term is about \(0.17\).

The residual plot of this fitted model shows a randomness band centered about 0 with constant scatter, so the equality of variance seems to be satisfied here. The distribution is normally distributed. There are no unduly influential points. Therefore, all assumptions of this model are satisfied.

This model only explained about \(61\%\) of the variation in the number of cyclists, so it is not a very good model for prediction.

2.5 Referring on your graphs and model, discuss whether rain has a big impact on the number of people cycling in Auckland.

  • The plots in Section 2.3 indicate that, overall, there is a negative relationship between the number of cyclists and the amount of precipitation in Auckland from 2016 to 2018. The number of cyclists seems to decrease as the rainfall increases. Moreover, the number of cyclists decreases more significantly when the rainfall increases from \(0\) to \(50mm\).

  • The term total_amount_mm is significant in the fitted model cyclists.fit (P-value \(\approx 0\)), so there is very strong evidence that rain has an impact on the number of cyclists in Auckland.

  • With \(95\%\) confidence, keeping all the other variables constant, we estimate that the expected number of cyclists decreases somewhere between \(212\) and \(246\) units for each \(1mm\) precipitation increase in Auckland.

  • Therefore, the variable rain significantly impacts the number of people cycling in Auckland based on the plots and the fitted model above.
